result.execSummary:
The defendant Danny R Rankin was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Case called at 1:22 pm [Clerk SH]
[Reserve Judge Mark Frankel presiding for BrIV]
Defendant Danny R Rankin in court with Attorney Charles Bennett Penwell. DA Susan Victoria Happ appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
DA Happ submits victim impact statement
State files AMENDED information-Service of the Amended Information admitted; reading waived

Constitutional rights given; plea of "Guilty" entered on Counts #1 & #2; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; Court finds the plea has been entered freely, voluntarily, intelligently and accepts the plea, finds Defendant guilty, orders JOC entered.
Sentencing arguments by DA Happ; Statements by Jeremy Karlinsky; Sentencing arguments by Atty Penwell

On Count #1, the Court sentences Defendant to:
--serve 5 days in Jefferson County Jail, with Huber/Work-Release privileges; to commence 3/6/15 by 6:00 pm
--1 day credit for time already served given
--pay costs of $243 + $200 DNA Surcharge = $443 + Atty fees; due in $75 increments as currently ordered for pay plan on Attorney fees; non-payment results in a 9 day jail term with Huber privileges, consecutive

On Count #2, the Court sentences the Defendant to pay a fine of $500 + costs = $883 + $200 DNA Surcharge = $1083;  due in $75 increments as currently ordered for pay plan on Attorney fees; Non-payment results in a 22 day jail term, with Huber privileges consecutive.

Defendant Danny R Rankin appears in custody, via video, from the Jefferson County Jail with Attorney Elizabeth F. Svehlek. Public Service Special Prosecutor, Melanie Flint appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Right to counsel given; constructive waiver of counsel warnings given.
Court finds the proceedings are sight and sound sufficient
